{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90e75e90-deca-4915-a92e-061b88ffcc7c","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, for consistency)\n\nAdd these properties so they apply to all three test projects:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Swaps the VSTest host for the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — each test project becomes a self-contained executable |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Lets `dotnet test` delegate to the new runner (otherwise only direct exe invocation works) |\n| `TrxReport` package | TRX output is no longer built-in; this extension restores it |\n\n## 2. Each `.csproj` — no changes needed\n\nThe properties above cover everything. If you already have a `Directory.Build.props` with other content, merge the snippet into it. If any project sets `<OutputType>` to something else, remove that override.\n\n## 3. CI command\n\nYour existing command works as-is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --logger trx\n```\n\nThe `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` bridge translates VSTest-style `--logger trx` into the platform-native equivalent automatically.\n\n## Summary of the migration\n\n- **Add 3 MSBuild properties + 1 package** in a shared `Directory.Build.props` — zero per-project edits.\n- **CI command stays the same.**\n- Each test project now compiles to an `.exe` that hosts Microsoft.Testing.Platform directly, removing the VSTest layer.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"461d798f-1d6c-4758-adf2-336d8e4e2896","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Enable Microsoft.Testing.Platform in each test project (or better, in a Directory.Build.props for consistency)\n2. **CI command**: Update the `dotnet test` command\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0, the migration involves:\n\n1. Adding `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each project, or preferably a shared `Directory.Build.props`\n\n\n2. Adding `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to keep `dotnet test` working as expected\n3. The TRX logger command-line syntax will need adjustment when running tests through the new platform\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0 specifically, I need to clarify the TRX reporting setup. With the Microsoft.Testing.Platform integration, TRX output requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package as a dependency. The MSTest 3.8.0 packages themselves provide the runner when `EnableMSTestRunner` is true and `OutputType` is set to `Exe`, but the TRX extension is separate. Setting `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` to true ensures the whole setup works with `dotnet test`. I need to figure out the right CI command syntax when `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is enabled—whether `--logger trx` gets properly translated or if I should use `--report-trx` instead with the new testing platform.","outputTokens":1584,"requestId":"702F:3F23E5:E29559D:F8B4091:69F2A765"},"id":"262a20ab-d23b-4e4b-91ea-81dd77b8dabe","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:51:16.511Z","parentId":"8dc1e7fa-953c-49ca-80b8-21572c030840"}
